  <div class="container py-5" style="max-width:860px;">

    <h1 class="fw-bold mb-1">What is Tokenization?</h1>
    <p class="text-muted mb-5">A plain-language guide to how large language models read and process text.</p>

    <!-- ── Section 1 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-primary text-white">1</span>
        The Core Idea
      </h2>
      <p>
        Computers can only process numbers — not words. Before a large language model can read your text, it must first
        break it into small, numbered chunks called <strong>tokens</strong>. This process is called
        <strong>tokenization</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        A token is usually a word, part of a word, a punctuation mark, or a short sequence of characters.
        For example, the sentence <em>"Tokenization is fun!"</em> might become four tokens:
      </p>
      <div class="token-demo d-flex flex-wrap gap-1 mb-3 p-3 rounded bg-white border">
        <span class="token-chip color-0">Token</span>
        <span class="token-chip color-1">ization</span>
        <span class="token-chip color-2"> is</span>
        <span class="token-chip color-3"> fun</span>
        <span class="token-chip color-4">!</span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-muted small">Each coloured chip above is one token as seen by an OpenAI model.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 2 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-success text-white">2</span>
        Why Not Just Use Words?
      </h2>
      <p>
        Splitting on spaces seems obvious, but it has serious problems:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Languages like Chinese and Japanese have no spaces between words.</li>
        <li>Rare or misspelled words would each need their own vocabulary entry, making the vocabulary enormous.</li>
        <li>Word pieces like <em>-ing</em>, <em>un-</em>, or <em>-tion</em> carry their own meaning — capturing them
            as sub-word tokens helps the model generalise to new words it has never seen.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Sub-word tokenization (used by all modern LLMs) strikes a balance: common words are one token, while rare or
        long words are split into familiar pieces.
      </p>
      <div class="alert alert-info d-flex gap-2 align-items-start">
        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb-fill fs-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-1"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> In English, 1 token ≈ 4 characters or ¾ of a word.
          100 tokens ≈ 75 words. A 1,000-word essay is roughly 1,300 tokens.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="alert alert-success d-flex gap-2 align-items-start">
        <i class="bi bi-speedometer2 fs-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-1"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Why sequence compression matters for LLMs:</strong> A model's attention mechanism has a cost
          proportional to the <em>square</em> of sequence length. If tokenization reduces 10,000 characters down
          to 2,500 tokens (4× compression), the attention computation becomes roughly 16× cheaper — not 4×.
          This is the core computational reason tokenization exists.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 3 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-warning text-dark">3</span>
        How BPE Tokenization Works
      </h2>
      <p>
        Most modern LLMs use <strong>Byte Pair Encoding (BPE)</strong>, originally a data-compression algorithm.
        Here's the idea in three steps:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Start with individual bytes.</strong> Every character (and its UTF-8 byte representation) is a
          valid token, so the model can always handle any input — even emoji or code.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Count the most frequent pairs.</strong> Look at all adjacent character pairs in a large training
          corpus and record how often each pair appears.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Merge the most common pair.</strong> Replace the most frequent pair with a single new token.
          Repeat until the vocabulary reaches a target size (typically 50,000–200,000 tokens).
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The result is a vocabulary where frequent sequences like <code>"ing"</code>, <code>" the"</code>, or
        <code>" function"</code> are single tokens, while rare sequences stay split into smaller pieces.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 4 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-danger text-white">4</span>
        Tokens and the Context Window
      </h2>
      <p>
        LLMs have a <strong>context window</strong> — a maximum number of tokens they can consider at once
        (both your input prompt <em>and</em> the model's output). If your text exceeds this limit, it gets
        cut off and the model loses earlier context.
      </p>
      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table class="table table-bordered table-sm align-middle">
          <thead class="table-dark">
            <tr>
              <th>Model</th>
              <th>Context Window</th>
              <th>Approx. pages of text</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>GPT-3.5 Turbo</td><td>16,385 tokens</td><td>~12 pages</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GPT-4o</td><td>128,000 tokens</td><td>~96 pages</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Claude 3.5 Sonnet</td><td>200,000 tokens</td><td>~150 pages</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Gemini 1.5 Pro</td><td>2,000,000 tokens</td><td>~1,500 pages</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Llama 3 (70B)</td><td>128,000 tokens</td><td>~96 pages</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 5 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-secondary text-white">5</span>
        Why Token Count Affects Cost
      </h2>
      <p>
        Commercial LLM APIs charge per token — not per character, word, or request. There are usually two prices:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Input tokens</strong> — the tokens in your prompt (usually cheaper).</li>
        <li><strong>Output tokens</strong> — the tokens the model generates (usually 3–5× more expensive).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This means that using precise, concise prompts saves money. Rephrasing a 500-token prompt to 200 tokens
        can cut costs by 60% on the input side.
      </p>
      <div class="alert alert-warning d-flex gap-2 align-items-start">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle-fill fs-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-1"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Watch out for system prompts.</strong> If your application adds a long system prompt to every
          request, those tokens are billed on every single call. Keeping system prompts short compounds savings
          across millions of API calls.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 6 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-info text-dark">6</span>
        Different Models, Different Tokenizers
      </h2>
      <p>
        Each LLM family uses its own tokenizer trained on its own vocabulary. The same text will produce a
        different number of tokens on different models:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>OpenAI</strong> uses <em>tiktoken</em> with the <code>cl100k_base</code> vocabulary (GPT-4, GPT-3.5)
            and <code>o200k_base</code> (GPT-4o, o1, o3).</li>
        <li><strong>Anthropic</strong> Claude uses a BPE tokenizer with a ~100,000 token vocabulary.</li>
        <li><strong>Meta Llama 2</strong> uses a SentencePiece BPE tokenizer with 32,000 tokens.</li>
        <li><strong>Meta Llama 3</strong> upgraded to a 128,000-token vocabulary for better multilingual support.</li>
        <li><strong>Mistral</strong> models share the Llama 2 tokenizer (32,000 token vocabulary).</li>
        <li><strong>Google Gemini</strong> uses a proprietary SentencePiece tokenizer (vocabulary size not publicly
            disclosed).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Use the <a href="/">Tokenizer tool</a> on this site to see exactly how each model splits your text.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Section 7 ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="h4 fw-semibold mb-3">
        <span class="section-icon bg-dark text-white">7</span>
        Practical Tips
      </h2>
      <div class="row g-3">
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-scissors me-2 text-danger"></i>Trim your prompts</h6>
              <p class="card-text small text-muted">Remove redundant context, boilerplate instructions, and
              repeated examples. Every saved token reduces latency and cost.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-translate me-2 text-primary"></i>Non-English text is denser</h6>
              <p class="card-text small text-muted">Languages with non-Latin scripts (Arabic, Chinese, Korean) often
              use more tokens per word than English, because the vocabulary was built primarily on English text.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-code-slash me-2 text-success"></i>Code is token-heavy</h6>
              <p class="card-text small text-muted">Whitespace, indentation, and punctuation all consume tokens.
              Minifying code before sending it to an API can meaningfully reduce token count.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h6 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-bar-chart me-2 text-warning"></i>Count before you send</h6>
              <p class="card-text small text-muted">Use the <a href="/">Tokenizer</a> to measure your prompts before
              sending them. This helps you stay within context limits and budget.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-5">
      <h2 class="d-flex align-items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="section-icon bg-primary text-white">8</span>
        Understanding the Statistics Dashboard
      </h2>
      <p>After tokenizing any text, a <strong>Detailed Statistics</strong> panel appears below the summary cards. Each tile explains a different aspect of how your text maps to tokens.</p>

      <div class="row g-4 mt-1">

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-window-stack text-primary me-2"></i>Context Window Used</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Shows what percentage of the model's maximum context window your text occupies, with a colour-coded progress bar (green → yellow → red). This is the most practical health-check before sending a request: exceeding 100 % means the model will truncate or refuse your input.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-lightning-charge text-success me-2"></i>Attention Cost Savings</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Transformer attention scales as <strong>O(n²)</strong> in sequence length. By compressing <em>n</em> characters into fewer tokens the cost multiplier is <strong>(chars ÷ tokens)²</strong>. A ratio of 4 chars/token means attention is 16× cheaper than processing raw characters — a direct measure of tokenization efficiency.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-fingerprint text-info me-2"></i>Unique Token IDs</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">The count of <em>distinct</em> token IDs used. A high unique percentage means rich, varied vocabulary; a high repetition rate (100 % − unique %) signals repetitive content. Repetitive text can sometimes be compressed further by prompt engineering or summarisation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-rulers text-warning me-2"></i>Average Token Length</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">The mean number of Unicode characters per token. Common English words average ~3–5 chars/token with GPT-style BPE. Short tokens (e.g. punctuation, spaces) lower this number; long compound words or rare terms raise it. The shortest and longest tokens in the text are shown for quick inspection.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-fonts text-secondary me-2"></i>Words &amp; Words per Token</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Word count estimated by whitespace splitting. The <em>words-per-token</em> ratio captures vocabulary density: prose typically sits near 0.6–0.9, code closer to 0.3–0.5, and single-character languages (Chinese, Japanese) can go well below 0.3.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-chat-text text-danger me-2"></i>Sentences &amp; Tokens per Sentence</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Sentences are approximated by splitting on <code>.!?</code>. The tokens-per-sentence figure helps size prompts for tasks like summarisation or translation where per-sentence granularity matters. Aim for a tokens/sentence ratio that fits comfortably within the model's output limit.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-hdd text-primary me-2"></i>Input Size &amp; Byte Ratio</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Compares the UTF-8 byte size of the raw text against the byte size of the token ID array (each ID stored as a 32-bit uint32 = 4 bytes). A byte ratio above 1 means the token sequence is <em>smaller</em> than the original text — useful for assessing wire-transfer efficiency.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-6">
          <div class="card h-100 border-0 shadow-sm">
            <div class="card-body">
              <h5 class="card-title"><i class="bi bi-percent text-success me-2"></i>Token Density</h5>
              <p class="card-text small">Tokens expressed as a percentage of characters: <code>tokens ÷ chars × 100</code>. A lower density (e.g. 20–30 %) means the tokenizer is packing many characters per token and the text is being compressed well. Higher density (near 100 %) means almost every character is its own token — typical of unusual scripts or adversarial inputs.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="text-center mt-5">
      <a href="/" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">
        <i class="bi bi-braces me-2"></i>Try the Tokenizer
      </a>
    </div>

  </div>

  <footer class="text-center text-muted py-3 small border-top mt-4">
